Author definition of units: % mean relative density in feces samples
Author definition of methods: fecal samples were collected once per month, stored in paper sacks, air-dried for 3 days and overn-dried at 60C for 24 hours
Author explaination of grouping: Thomson's gazelle was a grazer during wet season and a browser dry season
Author explaination of sample size: The samples of faeces were collected once per month. Wet season samples were taken from March through June and dry season from July through September. On the day of sampling, the researchers scouted the study area looking for fresh pellet piles of either type of gazelle. From each pellet pile, two pellets were picked. A total of ten pellet piles per gazelle species were identified. A total of 20 pellets were therefore collected per each sampling day.
Reported Study Site Location: Athi-Kapiti ecosystem; 80km south of Nairobi along Nairobi-Namanga highway
Author reported habitat/biome: vegetation consists primarily of scattered trees and open grasslands
Citation (abrv): Ngugi, Kilonzo, JM, and SM, Seasonal Botanical Characteristics, 581-588

Author explaination of sample size: The samples of faeces were collected once per month. Wet season samples were taken from March through June and dry season from July through September. On the day of sampling, the researchers scouted the study area looking for fresh pellet piles of either type of gazelle. From each pellet pile, two pellets were picked. A total of ten pellet piles per gazelle species were identified. A total of 20 pellets were therefore collected per each sampling day.
Reported Study Site Location: Athi-Kapiti ecosystem; 80km south of Nairobi along Nairobi-Namanga highway
Author reported habitat/biome: vegetation consists primarily of scattered trees and open grasslands
Citation (abrv): Ngugi, Kilonzo, JM, and SM, Seasonal Botanical Characteristics, 581-588

Units/metric diet is reported: Important food items expressed as percentages
Author definition of units: Food items found in the rumen of 68 mountain gazelle during 1972-3...the mountain gazelle's diet is composed of diverse plant species
Author definition of methods: the contents of 68 rumens were examined...about six gazelles were collected each month within the study area
Author explaination of grouping: Grasses and forbs constitute a major part of the diet during the whole year. ALthough the feeding habits vary according to seasonal plant growth
Author explaination of sample size: From September 1972 through September 1973, about six gazelles were collected each month within the study area. The contents of 68 rumens were examined.
Author reported habitat/biome: the climate is semi-arid, representing the transition between the Mediterranean and the Itano-Turanian phytogeographical zones with an annual rainfall of 300mm
Citation (abrv): Loggers, C. 1990. Food habits and population characteristics of dorcas gazelles and distributions and statuses of wild ungulates in Morocco. The University of Montana

Author definition of units: Proportional contribution of each grass species at each foraging site was calculated by dividing the number of grazed tufts of each species by the total number of grazed tufts of all grass species within that foraging site.
Author definition of methods: A foragin site was defined as the entire area where the animals were observed to have been feeding for at least 15 minutes. A quadrat was placed over an area of freshly cropped grass and each species was noted and identified.
Author explaination of grouping: To assess changes in diet and habitat use over the seasonal cycle the data collection period was sub-divided into two seasons in accordance with the floods and rainfall: Low water season (September - February); High water season (March - August).
Author explaination of sample size: The general study area was divided into five intensive study sites based on the locations of puku and lechwe. Study sites were then sub-divided into quarters
Author reported habitat/biome: Floodplain grasslands
Citation (abrv): O'Shaughnessy, 2010

Author definition of units: Proportional contribution of each grass species at each foraging site was calculated by dividing the number of grazed tufts of each species by the total number of grazed tufts of all grass species within that foraging site.
Author definition of methods: A foragin site was defined as the entire area where the animals were observed to have been feeding for at least 15 minutes. A quadrat was placed over an area of freshly cropped grass and each species was noted and identified.
Author explaination of grouping: To assess changes in diet and habitat use over the seasonal cycle the data collection period was sub-divided into two seasons in accordance with the floods and rainfall: Low water season (September - February); High water season (March - August).
Author explaination of sample size: The general study area was divided into five intensive study sites based on the locations of puku and lechwe. Study sites were then sub-divided into quarters

Author explaination of grouping: To assess changes in diet and habitat use over the seasonal cycle the data collection period was sub-divided into two seasons in accordance with the floods and rainfall: Low water season (September - February); High water season (March - August).
Author explaination of sample size: The general study area was divided into five intensive study sites based on the locations of puku and lechwe. Study sites were then sub-divided into quarters
Author reported habitat/biome: Floodplain grasslands

Author explaination of grouping: To assess changes in diet and habitat use over the seasonal cycle the data collection period was sub-divided into two seasons in accordance with the floods and rainfall: Low water season (September - February); High water season (March - August).
Author explaination of sample size: The general study area was divided into five intensive study sites based on the locations of puku and lechwe. Study sites were then sub-divided into quarters
Author reported habitat/biome: Floodplain grasslands

Author explaination of grouping: To assess changes in diet and habitat use over the seasonal cycle the data collection period was sub-divided into two seasons in accordance with the floods and rainfall: Low water season (September - February); High water season (March - August).
Author explaination of sample size: The general study area was divided into five intensive study sites based on the locations of puku and lechwe. Study sites were then sub-divided into quarters
Author reported habitat/biome: Floodplain grasslands
Citation (abrv): O'Shaughnessy, 2010

Author definition of units: % from the total fragment area of all observed fragments
Author definition of methods: In Kansanka NP, the general collection of puku dung took place along the transect lines Puku-Loop. About 5 to 7g of each dung sample, i.e. about 8 to 10 pellets, was taken for preparation and entered analysis.
Author explaination of grouping: Diet composition and diet characteristics of the piku (Kobus vardonii) in Kasanka NP differentiating between sexes and between seasons
Author explaination of sample size: A total of 150 (sub) samples of dung were viewed under the microscope, which led to 15,000 observed fragments
Author reported habitat/biome: About 70% of the total area of Kasanka NP is covered by woodland. The largest part - about 80% - is miombo. Small patches of evergreen riverine gallery forests and wet evergreen swamp forest are also present.
If yes, list the common names here: Reedbuck, sable antelope, lichtenstein's hartebeest, african buffalo, impala, waterbuck
Citation (abrv): Rduch, Vera. Ecology and Population Status of the Puku Antelope
Notes: page 114 has data

Author definition of units: % plant parts in rumen contents
Author definition of methods: During every field-work period four grey rhebuck were shot. After thorough mixing, a sample of each animal's rumen contents was taken and preserved in 5% formalin.
Author explaination of grouping: NA
Author explaination of sample size: Field work for this study was done between February 1983 and February 1984. During this period the park was visited every second month. During every field-work period four grey rhebuc were shot.
Author reported habitat/biome: landscape consists of two plateau-like river terraces of the Bree River valley...mainly low shrubs with a scattered grass component
Citation (abrv): Diet of grey rhebuck in th e Bonte bok National Park, P.C. Beukes
